"### File Structure
```
CarRental/
│
├── app.py
├── data/
│   ├── vehicles.txt
│   ├── customers.txt
│   ├── locations.txt
│   ├── rentals.txt
│   ├── insurance.txt
│   └── reservations.txt
│
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── vehicle_search.html
│   ├── vehicle_details.html
│   ├── booking.html
│   ├── insurance_options.html
│   ├── rental_history.html
│   ├── reservations.html
│   ├── special_requests.html
│   └── locations.html
│
└── static/
    ├── css/
    │   └── styles.css
    ├── js/
    │   └── scripts.js
    └── images/
        └── (vehicle images, icons, etc.)
```

### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main backend Python application file. It will handle routing for all nine pages, process user inputs, read/write data from/to the local text files in the `data/` directory, and implement the core business logic such as searching vehicles, booking rentals, managing reservations, calculating prices, and handling insurance selections. Since the application is not very complex, consolidating backend logic into this single file is efficient and maintainable.

- **data/**  
  Directory containing all the local text files used for data storage as specified in the requirements. These files store vehicles, customers, locations, rentals, insurance plans, and reservations data in the defined pipe-separated format.

- **templates/**  
  Contains HTML template files for each of the nine pages of the web application. Each file corresponds to a page described in the requirements and includes the specified elements with their IDs for frontend rendering and interaction.

- **static/css/styles.css**  
  Stylesheet for the entire web application to ensure consistent and responsive UI design.

- **static/js/scripts.js**  
  JavaScript file to handle client-side interactivity such as button clicks, form validations, dynamic content updates, and navigation between pages.

- **static/images/**  
  Folder to store images used in the application, including vehicle photos, icons, and promotional banners.

This structure cleanly separates backend logic, data storage, frontend templates, and static assets, facilitating straightforward development, testing, and maintenance."

